Your instinct is right on the money — cut what's shared. Ranked by impact:

1. **Give comment analysis its own lightweight prompt** (fixes quality *and* is the single biggest cost lever). A ~10-line prompt asking only for `sentiment`, `relevance_score`, `ai_summary` needs a fraction of the output tokens the current one forces — no sub-scores, no fabricated sources, no steelman. This alone should cut per-comment cost by 70-90%.

2. **Batch all comments into one Gemini call instead of N.** Right now, analyzing a post with 5 comments = 6 separate Gemini requests, each paying the full prompt overhead again. One request with all comments + one shared instruction, returning an array, replaces N round-trips with 1 — this is probably your biggest total-cost fix for multi-comment posts.

3. **Skip re-analyzing comments that already have a recent, unchanged analysis.** Right now every "Analyze Post & Discussion" click re-analyzes *every* comment from scratch, even ones analyzed seconds ago — pure repeat spend if you click twice.

4. **Strip the unused `comments` array from the post-level payload** — the audit prompt never references it, so it's just wasted input tokens on every post analysis.

5. **Cap comment content length** sent per comment as a defensive ceiling (minor, but free).

